@Node "Player-input" "Chaos_english.guide/Player-input"
@Next "Setting games"
@Prev "Player-selection"
@Toc "Input-windows"

The Input-of-player-data-window
===============================

   When selecting one of the menu-items @{b}Players-Add@{ub} or @{b}Players-Modify@{ub}, this
window will appear. See @{"Players" Link "Players"}. It uses the following gadgets:

@{i}Name@{ui}
     The player's name is used, when pairing the first round. The players
     are sorted alphabetically by the program, therefore their names need
     to be entered in a uniform way. Suggested is last name, comma, first
     name, for example "Wiedmann, Jochen". See @{"Swiss pairing" Link "Swiss pairing"}.

     You @{i}must@{ui} enter a player's name and it must be unique! The program
     doesn't accept clicking the Ok-gadget without a name! If needed, use
     something like @{b}Miller, Joe (2)@{ub}.

@{i}Home address@{ui}
@{i}Phone@{ui}
     The player's addresses will not be needed in most cases. Of course
     they might be useful, if a tournament goes on for an extended period
     of time.

@{i}Chess-club@{ui}
     This will not be needed too in most cases. But you might wish to
     include this in the list of players.

@{i}Birthday@{ui}
     A players birthday is needed only when computing the DWZ-ratings. It
     @{i}must@{ui} be entered as dd.mm.yy or dd.mm.yyyy, where dd means day, mm
     means month and yy Year. I would like to use the excellent DOS-routine
     StrToDate, which might use the locale's date format instead of my own.
     But StrToDate fails when entering dates prior to 1.1.1978!

     The program checks birthdays before accepting them and rejects
     incorrect dates.

@{i}Rating@{ui}
     The rating is used to create an internal ranking, when pairing the
     first round (Swiss pairing only) and when computing the new DWZ of
     course. You might enter any national rating, for example USCF-rating
     instead, if they are sorted descending. (Better players have higher
     numbers.) Of course you must not mix ratings of different systems, you
     should convert them instead.

     Please notice that the official form of the DWZ is something like
     1834-23, which means a rating of 1834 resulting from 23 tournaments.
     Chaos accepts both the official and the short form 1834.

@{i}ELO@{ui}
     If players have an ELO-number, this rather than DWZ will be used by
     Chaos.  (This seems wise to me, but could be handled in a different
     manner.) Please notice, that ELO-numbers should not be entered, if
     national ratings and ELO-numbers aren't equivalent. For example
     players which have the same DWZ or ELO should be expected to have the
     same playing strength.

For all these string-gadgets please have a look at @{"Input-windows" Link "Input-windows"}.

@{i}Senior@{ui}
@{i}Junior@{ui}
@{i}Woman@{ui}
@{i}Junior (A)@{ui}
@{i}Junior (B)@{ui}
@{i}Junior (C)@{ui}
@{i}Junior (D)@{ui}
@{i}Junior (E)@{ui}
     If you want to make separate tables for special groups (for example
     you can give a prize to the best woman), but all players are paired in
     one group, you can use these gadgets to mark the groups. This doesn't
     affect the pairings, it just adds the possibiltyof creating separate
     tables for these groups. See @{"Table" Link "Output"}.


@EndNode

