Setting games
=============

   Under certain circumstances you might wish to force special pairings.
That's why this window appears before drawing the games of a new round in a
Swiss pairing tournament. I don't expect you want this in most cases and so
the window can be disabled using the menu item @{b}Setting games@{ub}.  See
@{"Setting games" Link "Preferences"}.

   To the left of the window you find the list of all players except for
withdrawn players. By double-clicking a players name you put him into the
list of set games on the right side of the window. Of course you need to
double-click another player to make a game. Chaos doesn't allow you to pair
players again. You will be asked, if you really want to pair players, if
both had one color in the last two rounds. Using the @{b}Delete@{ub} button you can
remove games.

   Normally Chaos should determine who will receive the white pieces. This
makes the pairings easier in the following rounds. However, this can be
changed using the cycle gadget below the list of players. In that case the
first player will receive the white pieces. (The order of setting is
meaningless otherwise.) Matches with colors determined are indicated by a
@{b}(cd)@{ub} (colors determined) behind the names.

   You can as well select a player for a one point bye: After all games have
been selected, double-click the player for the one point bye. (You select
an odd number of players.) Of course this isn't allowed, if the number of
active players is even or if the player already had an one point bye.


@EndNode

@Node "Result-input" "Chaos_english.guide/Result-input"
@Prev "Setting games"
@Toc "Input-windows"

The Input-of-results-window
===========================

   By selecting a subitem of @{b}Round-Input results@{ub} you create this window,
which shows a list of one round's games. (see @{"Input results" Link "Round"}) By using the
usual Arrow- and scrollbar-gadgets you might scroll this list.  There is
always one game, which is activated and therefore highlighted (Kickstart
3.x) or shown beneath the List (Kickstart 2.x). You might activate another
game by clicking it.

   Some other gadgets are placed below. By clicking the right ones (@{b}Played@{ub}
and @{b}Not played@{ub}) you tell the program, if a game really took place or was,
for example, forfeited. (Default is, that the game was played.) The gadgets
to the left (@{b}White wins@{ub}, @{b}Draw@{ub}, @{b}Black wins@{ub}, @{b}Result missing@{ub}) allow to enter
the game's result. (Default is, that the result is missing.)

   You may as well use the keyboard to enter results: The keys w (White
wins), d (Draw), b (Black wins), m (Result missing), p (Game played) and n
(Game not played) correspond to the gadgets above. The next game will
automatically be activated after a result was entered. This allows a rather
fast and comfortable input.


@EndNode

